-- Naphtha Crackers Shut for Scheduled Maintenance in Japan, Korea
-- B y   J a c o b   A d e l m a n
-- 2012-03-07T04:43:32Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2012-03-07/naphtha-crackers-shut-for-scheduled-maintenance-in-japan-korea.html
Tosoh Corp. (4042)  plans to shut its
493,000 metric-ton-a-year naphtha cracker in Yokkaichi for
scheduled maintenance on March 15.  The Tokyo-based company is among Japanese and South Korean
ethylene producers idling capacity for maintenance leading into
the second quarter of 2012. Tosohâ€™s Yokkaichi shutdown is
scheduled to last until April 15, Michael Hoover, a company
spokesman, said in an e-mail today.  Showa Denko KK (4004)  began reducing output by 200,000 tons a year
at its ethylene plant in Oita for scheduled maintenance today,
Nobuhiro Kato, a company spokesman, said by phone today from
Tokyo. The 691,000 ton-a-year unit was scheduled to return to
full capacity on March 29, he said.  Asahi Kasei Corp. (3407)  shut its 504,000 ton-a-year cracker in
Mizushima for scheduled maintenance on March 5, Mio Iwatsuki, a
company spokeswoman, said by phone yesterday from Tokyo. The
unit was scheduled to restart on April 16, she said.  In  South Korea ,  Yeochun NCC Co. (YENCCZ)  plans to shut its 578,000
ton-a-year Yeocheon No. 2 plant for maintenance from March 20 to
April 19, according to a company official who asked not to be
named because the information was confidential.  Honam Petrochemical Corp. (011170)  shut its 750,000 ton-a-year
Yeocheon plant on March 1 for maintenance and to expand its
capacity to 1 million metric tons a year, said a company
official, who also declined to be identified. The closure was
scheduled to last until April 10, the official said.  The following is a table of planned maintenance shutdowns
